  "prompt": "Why did India accept the Indus Water Treaty,1960?",
  "response": "India accepted the Indus Water Treaty of 1960 for several strategic and pragmatic reasons:\n\n1. Water Sharing Resolution\n- To resolve water-sharing disputes with Pakistan after partition\n- Provide a permanent solution to water allocation issues\n- Prevent potential water-related conflicts\n\n2. World Bank's Mediation\n- The treaty was negotiated with the World Bank's active mediation\n- Offered a mutually acceptable framework for water distribution\n- Provided international support and credibility\n\n3. Geopolitical Considerations\n- Demonstrated India's commitment to peaceful resolution of disputes\n- Reduced potential tensions with Pakistan\n- Enhanced India's diplomatic standing internationally\n\n4. Practical Water Management\n- Allocated specific rivers to each country\n- Western rivers (Indus, Jhelum, Chenab) to Pakistan\n- Eastern rivers (Ravi, Beas, Sutlej) to India\n\n5. Technical and Economic Aspects\n- Allowed for agricultural and hydroelectric development\n- Provided mechanisms for technical cooperation\n- Ensured predictable water resource management\n\n6. Post-Partition Reconciliation\n- Helped stabilize India-Pakistan relations\n- Reduced potential for immediate water-related conflicts\n- Established a framework for future negotiations\n\nThese factors collectively motivated India to accept the Indus Water Treaty in 1960.",
